## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates understanding of idempotency patterns and cross-service consistency in distributed payment systems. It tests knowledge of concurrency handling, retry mechanisms, and observability in mission-critical financial flows.

## Key Concepts
- Idempotency keys spanning multiple services (ledger, order, event bus)
- Cross-service data consistency and eventual consistency windows
- High-concurrency testing methodologies (k6, JMeter)
- Failure scenario simulation: ledger outages, event-bus delays
- Observability patterns: distributed tracing, metrics, and retry monitoring

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-test using k6-like script
import http from 'k6/http';
import { check } from 'k6';
export default function () {
  const url = 'https://api.example.com/payments/process';
  const payload = {
    amount: 100,
    currency: 'USD',
    'idempotency-key': 'test-key-123'
  };
  const params = {
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json',
      'Authorization': 'Bearer token'
    }
  };

  // Simulate high concurrency with identical keys
  const responses = http.batch(url.map(url => 
    http.post(url, JSON.stringify(payload), params)
  ));

  // Verify single processing
  check(responses, {
    'single successful response': (r) => r.filter(res => res.status === 200).length === 1,
    'duplicate responses rejected': (r) => r.filter(res => res.status === 409).length > 0
  });
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Assess foundational webhook testing skills: security, idempotency, and resilience in the face of downstream failures.

## Key Concepts

- Webhook security (signature verification)
- Idempotent processing with Idempotency-Key
- Retry/backoff semantics and 429 handling
- Fault tolerance with datastore outages

## Code Example

```javascript
// Example webhook handler skeleton
app.post('/webhooks/:provider', (req, res) => {
